            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415032856,
            "creation_date": 1415032856,
            "body": "<p>Create an interface with a <code>getStatus()<\/code> method and make all item classes implement it.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718759,
            "question_id": 26718643
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/tiSgr.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 983770,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1002790,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1002790/salih-erikci",
                "reputation": 5095,
                "display_name": "Salih Erikci",
                "accept_rate": 76
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415032989,
            "creation_date": 1415032989,
            "body": "<p>Create 2 interfaces for borrowed ones and returned ones.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public interface returnedItem(){\n   public String getLocation();\n   public void setLocation(String s);\n}\n\npublic interface borrowedItem(){\n   public Date getDue();\n   public void setDue(Date date);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718795,
            "question_id": 26718643
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/553151d388046abb418ab4972f653ce7?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 4530748,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 3681315,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3681315/kmac",
                "reputation": 115,
                "display_name": "kmac"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415033004,
            "creation_date": 1415033004,
            "body": "<p>One simple way to give all objects (bike, roller skates, etc) a borrowed or returned is to make a super class.<\/p>\n\n<p>Ex:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class Borrowable {\n    private boolean borrowed = false;\n\n    public borrow() {\n        borrowed = true;\n    }\n\n    public return() {\n        borrowed = false;\n    } \n\n    public isBorrowed() {\n        return borrowed;\n    }\n\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>If you extend this class with bike then you can call the borrowable methods without having to write the code over again.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718800,
            "question_id": 26718643
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/8wdJC.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2915411,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2498729,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2498729/but-im-not-a-wrapper-class",
                "reputation": 14436,
                "display_name": "But I&#39;m Not A Wrapper Class",
                "accept_rate": 69
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415033634,
            "creation_date": 1415033011,
            "body": "<p>Use an <code>interface<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>interface Item{\n    boolean isBorrowed();\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Then make <code>abstract<\/code> classes for all different items by implementing the <code>interface<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>abstract class Bike implements Item{\n    //code\n}\n\nabstract class RollerSkates implements Item{\n    //code\n}\n\n//etc.\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Now <code>extend<\/code> these <code>abstract<\/code> classes:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public class BorrowedBike extends Bike{\n    //code\n    //add additional field 'due date'\n    boolean isBorrowed(){\n        return true;\n    }\n}\n\npublic class ReturnedBike extends Bike{\n    //code\n   //add additional field 'location'\n    boolean isBorrowed(){\n        return false;\n    }\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718802,
            "question_id": 26718643,
            "last_edit_date": 1415033634
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/eNviq.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 5243963,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4190267,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4190267/indian",
                "reputation": 130,
                "display_name": "indian"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415033029,
            "creation_date": 1415033029,
            "body": "<p>what you can do is to create a class type for each item , \ncreate Item class which is a generic class , and inherit from it 2 sub-classes borrowed item and returned one<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>class Bike\n...\nclass Skates\n...\nclass Roller\n\nclass Item&lt;T&gt;\n...\nclass BorrowedItem&lt;T&gt; extends Item&lt;T&gt;\n...\nclass ReturnedItem&lt;T&gt; extends Item&lt;T&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718813,
            "question_id": 26718643
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/b9f2b86e6f65a8eddb71b2839d7b20c3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 2917357,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2500283,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2500283/divya",
                "reputation": 1485,
                "display_name": "Divya",
                "accept_rate": 92
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1415033170,
            "creation_date": 1415033170,
            "body": "<p>Instead of making <code>borrowed bike<\/code> and <code>returned bike<\/code> for bike sub class \nyou can follow an approach to make a class \n<code>item<\/code> with variable <code>nameOfItem<\/code> and <code>type<\/code> it can be either bike ,roller stakes or any other.\nIt will hold for an instance <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Name            status\nbike            returned\nroller stakes   borrowed\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 26718863,
            "question_id": 26718643
        }
